<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="199" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1064,2025]" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1064,1089]" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">Host plant.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="(Vahl) Hoffmans. et Link" authorityName="(Vahl) Hoffmans. et Link" box="[345,917,1064,1089]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Caprifoliaceae" genus="Pycnocomon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Dipsacales" pageId="4" pageNumber="199" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rutifolium">
<emphasis box="[345,613,1064,1089]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">Pycnocomon rutifolium</emphasis>
(Vahl) Hoffmans. et Link
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[935,1081,1064,1089]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Dipsacaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Dipsacales" pageId="4" pageNumber="199" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Dipsacaceae</taxonomicName>
), a perennial herb in Southern 
<collectingCountry box="[151,215,1100,1125]" name="Spain" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">Spain</collectingCountry>
on maritime sands. It is a characteristic species of dry habitat. It should be mentioned that the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Hoffmans. et Link" authorityName="Hoffmans. et Link" box="[151,508,1136,1161]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Caprifoliaceae" genus="Pycnocomon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Dipsacales" pageId="4" pageNumber="199" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,295,1137,1160]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">Pycnocomon</emphasis>
Hoffmans. et Link
</taxonomicName>
is now included in the 
<taxonomicName box="[769,932,1136,1161]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Caprifoliaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Dipsacales" pageId="4" pageNumber="199" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Caprifoliaceae</taxonomicName>
by some botanists.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1064,2025]" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,520,1172,1197]" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">Relation to the host plant.</emphasis>
The mite was found in all stages of development in the erinea on the leaflets. Definite symptoms were observed: the plant became swollen and distorted with visible erinea on the margin of the leaflets, giving yellowish appearance to the plant (
<figureCitation box="[714,852,1244,1269]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 3" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1002,1025]" captionTargetBox="[169,1418,156,980]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[157,1429,155,981]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 3. Symptoms of Aceria pycnocomi sp. nov. on Pycnocomon rutifolium. (Photo: Iňigo Sánchez)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/400852/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">Figures 2–3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
